08461nam a22010215i 9789048544509DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485445097 a10.1515/97890485445092doi  a(DE-B1597)542044  a(OCoLC)1143823963  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0580002bisacsh04aThe Aesthetics of Global Protest :bVisual Culture and Communication /ced. by Hande Eslen-Ziya, Olu Jenzen, Umut Korkut, Aidan McGarry, Itir Erhart. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (298 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aProtest and Social Movements ;v1900tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface: Devisualize -- tIntroduction: The Aesthetics of Global Protest : Visual Culture and Communication -- tPart I: Performance, Art and Politics -- t1 Queer Visual Activism in South Africa -- t2 The Use of Visibility in Contentious Events in Northern Ireland -- t3 Maybe, We Will Benefit from Our Neighbour's Good Fortune : An Exhibition on Collectivity, Community, and Dialogue in Turkey -- t4 Political Street Art in Social Mobilization : A Tale of Two Protests in Argentina -- t5 Archiving Dissent : (Im)material Trajectories of Political Street Art in Istanbul and Athens -- t6 The Introvert's Protest : Handwriting the Constitution and the Performance of Politics -- tPart II: Visual Activism and Digital Culture -- t7 Photography and Protest in Israel/Palestine : The Activestills Online Archive -- t8 Drones, Cinema, and Protest in Thailand -- t9 Bearing Witness to Authoritarianism and Commoning through Video Activism and Political Film-making after the Gezi Protests -- t10 Music Videos as Protest Communication: The Gezi Park Protest on YouTube -- t11 The Activist Chroniclers of Occupy Gezi : Counterposing Visibility to Injustice -- t12 When Twitter Got #woke : Black Lives Matter, DeRay McKesson, Twitter, and the Appropriation of the Aesthetics of Protest -- tPart III: Conclusion -- t13 Conclusion : Reflections on Protest and Political Transformation since 1789 -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aProtestors across the world use aesthetics in order to communicate their ideas and ensure their voices are heard. This book looks at protest aesthetics, which we consider to be the visual and performative elements of protest, such as images, symbols, graffiti, art, as well as the choreography of protest actions in public spaces. Through the use of social media, protestors have been able to create an alternative space for people to engage with politics that is more inclusive and participatory than traditional politics. This volume focuses on the role of visual culture in a highly mediated environment and draws on case studies from Europe, Thailand, South Africa, USA, Argentina, and the Middle East in order to demonstrate how protestors use aesthetics to communicate their demands and ideas. It examines how digital media is harnessed by protestors and argues that all protest aesthetics are performative and communicative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aConflict and Peace. 4aDigital and Social Media. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 4aSociology and Social History. 4aUrban Cultures. 7aART / Graffiti & Street Art.2bisacsh  aVisual culture, protest, communication, performance, digital.1 aAulich, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErhart, Itir, econtributor.4ctb4https://i